= section "Features" do
  %p Novegradian is a highly fusional inflecting language, meaning information tends to be densely packed in a relatively small set of affixes. A single suffix #{t "-м", "-m"}, for instance, may mark a verb as being in the present tense and as having a subject that is both first person and singular.
  %p Like other Indo-European languages, verbs are conjugated through adding various affixes to a verb stem. All stems have an inherent conjugation class, which is arbitrary, but determines the types of endings it receives (for instance, the 1st and athematic conjugations mark the #{abbrev '1sg'} Present/Future with #{t "-м", "-m"}, while the 2nd and 3rd conjugations use #{t "-ун", "-un"}). Both prefixes (added before the stem) and suffixes (added after the stem) are used. Most verbs also have a theme vowel, which is largely connected to the conjugation class and appears immediately after the root in the present/future tense.
  %p The stem consists of a root and zero or more derivational affixes. The root is the most basic unit providing semantic meaning to the verb. For many verbs, typically termed “primitive”, the stem and root are one and the same (e.g., #{t "*рѣѕ-", "*rědz-"} “say, read aloud”). Far more, however, include a derivational affix or formative, which slightly modifies the meaning of the root and therefore the stem as a whole (e.g., #{t "*о-рѣѕ-", "*o-rědz-"} “promise”); this type of stem is known as “derived”.
  %p Many verbs actually have two stems, one known as the “infinitive stem” and the other as the “present/future stem”, and the two may have different theme vowels. All verb forms are predictably based on one of the two stems.
  %p The majority of the verb forms to be described in this section are finite, meaning they convey tense/aspect/modality information. Such verbs conjugate in agreement with their grammatical subject, although the features marked vary across different verb forms; some forms agree  with the subject’s person (1st, 2nd, or 3rd) and number (Singular, Dual, or Plural), while others agree in number and gender (Masculine, Feminine, or Neuter).
  %p Independently of their environment, finite verbs mark two tenses (Past and a combined Present/Future), two primary aspects#{footnote} (Perfective and Imperfective), and three moods (Indicative, Subjunctive, and Imperative).
  %p Non-finite verb forms lack tense and mood marking, although they maintain aspect. Two are pseudo-nominal (the Infinitive and the Supine), three are pseudo-adjectival (the three participles), and two are pseudo-adverbial (the two adverbial participles). The infinitive is considered the citation form of all Novegradian verbs; unless otherwise noted, verbs will be cited in their infinitive form throughout this text.
  %p Stems are inherently transitive or intransitive. Change in valency typically involves a periphrastic construction, a derivational operation, or a change in voice, of which Novegradian has three: Active, Passive, and Middle. Some transitive verbs, however, allow for the direct object to simply be omitted or implied.

= section "Verb Roots and Conjugations" do
  %p Novegradian has four conjugations. Three of these are thematic—A, E, I—and one is athematic, although this last group only contains four verbs: #{t "буити", "buíti"} “be”, #{t "ѣсти", "iě́sti"} “eat”, #{t "вѣсти", "vě́sti"} “know”, and #{t "дати", "dáti"} “give”.#{footnote}
  %p Each verb only has a present/future and past tense formed through inflection, as well as several non-finite forms (the infinitive, supine, and participles). The perfective form of an imperfective verb is generally made by adding a prefix or using a suppletive verb.
  %p A-Class verbs (first conjugation) tend to be quite regular, while I-class (second conjugation) and E-class (third conjugation) verbs are prone to consonant mutations in some forms.
  %p Most native verb roots consist of only one syllable, sometimes two, or sometimes less than one. Individual verb stems can be stem-stressed, ending-stressed, or mobile-stressed. Stem-stressed verbs are usually accented on the same syllable in the stem, and ending-stressed verbs on the first syllable after the stem. Mobile-stressed verbs fall into many subcategories depending on the conjugation and form involved.
  %p While the conjugation classes no longer have well-defined meanings, there are a few tendencies that can be observed, likely carryovers from Pre-Proto-Slavic or Proto-Indo-European:
  %ul
    %li Almost all non-derived first conjugation verbs are imperfective, and the majority of imperfective verbs are first conjugation.
    %li Many verbs denoting sounds or derived from onomatopoeia are second conjugation and have -ѣ- as the infinitive theme vowel (or have an affricate or palatalized fricative + -а-, which historically comes from an earlier *ě): #{t "криѕати", "kridzáti"} “shout”, #{t "храпѣти", "hrápěti"} “snore”, #{t "шумѣти", "śumě́ti"} “be noisy”.
    %li The vast majority of second conjugation verbs with -ѣ- as the infinitive theme vowel are intransitive. Many have transitive historical counterparts with -и-, though sound changes predating Common Slavic have since obscured these pairs: #{t "горѣти", "gorě́ti"} “burn (#{abbrev 'intr'})”, #{t "жарити", "źáriti"} “make jealous”#{footnote}; #{t "родѣти", "rodě́ti"} “blush”#{footnote}, #{t "рудити", "rudíti"} “embarrass”#{footnote}.
    %li Third conjugation verbs that appear to have the infinitive theme vowel -ѣ- actually have the stative suffix #{t "-ѣй-", "-ěi-"}. These verbs are typically derived (fairly transparently) from nouns or adjectives and mean “be ADJ” or “have NOUN”: #{t "омѣти", "omě́ti"} “know how to” (from #{t "оме", "óme"} “intellect”). This subgroup was once far more common and productive, but it now consists only of a few relics.
    %li Third conjugation verbs with the suffix -н- (-на- in the infinitive) are always perfective. This suffix generally marks very abrupt actions or, when derived from adjectives, transformation. This suffix is sometimes called the “punctual”.

= section "The Infinitive" do
  %p The infinitive is formed from the verb stem using the suffix #{t "-ти", "-ti"}, or less commonly, #{t "-йкьи", "-ikji"}. This ending is never stressed.
  %p However, there are a number of factors that make the infinitive more complex to form. Many, though not all verbs have a distinct ‘infinitive stem’, which differs slightly from the stem + thematic vowel used to form the present/future tense (the present/future stem).

  = section "A-Conjugation Infinitive" do
    %p The A-Conjugation infinitive is extremely regular, formed with the ending #{t "-ати", "-ati"} attached to the verb stem. This theme vowel may be either stressed or unstressed. In the very frequently-seen deperfective pattern ending in #{t "-ов-ати", "ov-áti"}, the theme vowel is always stressed.
    %ul
      %li *работ- → #{t "работати", "rabótati"} “to work” (stem stressed)
      %li *дѣл- → #{t "дѣлати", "dě́lati"} “to make, do” (stem stressed)
      %li *цид- → #{t "цидати", "cidáti"} “to read” (ending stressed)
      %li *егр- → #{t "еграти", "iegráti"} “to play” (ending stressed)
      %li *по-каз-ов- → #{t "показовати", "pokazováti"} “to show, demonstrate” (deperfective)
      %li *со-цед-ов- → #{t "соцедовати", "socedováti"} “to consider” (deperfective)

  = section "I-Conjugation Infinitive" do
    %p The I-Conjugation infinitive is formed fairly regularly using one of the endings #{t "-ити", "-iti"} or #{t "-ѣти", "-ěti"}. The -ити type is far more common, but any difference in meaning between the two endings was lost many centuries ago. This choice of endings can be particular confounding due to the fact that, with the exception of ending-stressed verbs, the both are pronounced identically. The ě-type is sometimes referred to as the stative pattern, although this name is purely historical.
    %ul
      %li *мѣр- → #{t "мѣрити", "mě́riti"} “to measure” (stem stressed, i-type)
      %li *вар- → #{t "варити", "váriti"} “to boil” (stem stressed, i-type)
      %li *рѣѕ- → #{t "рѣѕити", "rědzíti"} “to say, read aloud” (ending stressed, i-type)
      %li *луб- → #{t "лубити", "lubíti"} “to love” (hysterodynamic, i-type)
      %li *вид- → #{t "видѣти", "víděti"} “to see” (stem stressed, ě-type)
      %li *бол- → #{t "болѣти", "bolě́ti"} “to hurt, ache” (ending stressed, ě-type)
    %p The ě-type has a variant #{t "-ати", "-ati"}, which predictably occurs after stems ending in /sʲ zʲ ts dz j/, and unpredictably after consonants that historically were once of these five.
    %ul
      %li *криѕ- → #{t "криѕати", "kridzáti"} “to shout” (palatal stem, ě-type)
      %li *держ- → #{t "держати", "derźáti"} “hold” (palatal stem, ě-type)
      %li *стой- → #{t "стояти", "stoiáti"} “stand” (palatal stem, ě-type)
      %li *слих- → #{t "слихати", "slíhati"} “hear” (palatal stem, ě-type)#{footnote}
    %p One other subtype with only a handful of verbs is known as the sonantic stem, where the stem historically ends in a sonant /r l n/. These stems historically had no theme vowel, just taking a bare suffix #{t "-ти", "-ti"}, but later this sonant underwent metathesis with the preceding vowel. These verbs thus appear to end in a variety of vowels in the infinitive, when the stem actually is consonantal.
    %ul
      %li *пер- → #{t "прети", "préti"} “to force” (sonantic stem)
      %li *сни- → #{t "снити(ш)", "sníti(ś)"} “to dream” (sonantic stem)
      %li *довел- → #{t "довлѣти", "dovlě́ti"} “to suffice” (sonantic stem)

  = section "E-Conjugation Infinitive" do
    %p The E-Conjugation infinitive is by far the most complex to form. It is typically formed with the suffix #{t "-ати", "-ati"} or just the themeless suffix #{t "-ти", "-ti"}, although this latter form tends to cause many stem alterations when it comes in contact with the bare stem.
    %p When the suffix -ати is used, it is almost always stressed, no matter whether the stem is usually ending-stressed in other forms or not. This ending is predictably used whenever the stem contains the punctual suffix -н-.
    %ul
      %li *пиз- → #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “to write” (stem stressed)
      %li *еск- → #{t "ескати", "ieskáti"} “to look for” (stem stressed)
      %li *рѣз- → #{t "рѣзати", "rězáti"} “to cut” (stem stressed)
      %li *тег- → #{t "тегати", "tegáti"} “to weave” (ending stressed)
      %li *наш-н- → #{t "нашнати", "naśnáti"} “to begin, start” (punctual)
    %p Dental stems are stems ending in one of the dental consonants /t d s z/, which may come in direct contact with the infinitive suffix without a theme vowel. However, stem-final *t and *d will both lenite to /s/ in this position.
    %ul
      %li *нес- → #{t "нести", "nésti"} “to carry” (dental stem in *s)
      %li *гриз- → #{t "гризти", "grízti"} “to gnaw” (dental stem in *z)
      %li *мет- → #{t "мести", "mésti"} “to sweep” (dental stem in *t)
      %li *крад- → #{t "красти", "krásti"} “to steal” (dental stem in *d)
    %p Sonantic stems, much like in the I-Conjugation, end in one of the sonants /r l n/ and undergo metathesis in the infinitive. Historically the I-Conjugation sonantic stems were also E-Conjugation, but there has been a general trend towards conversion to the I-Conjugation.
    %ul
      %li *мол- → #{t "млети", "mléti"} “to grind” (sonantic stem)
      %li *про-кол- → #{t "проклати", "prokláti"} “to stab” (sonantic stem)
    %p In velar stems, which end in /k g/, the velar consonant and infinitive ending palatalize and merge into an unanalyzable suffix #{t "-кьи", "-kji"}. In addition, the vowel immediately preceding gains a /j/ off-glide.
    %ul
      %li *пек- → #{t "пейкьи", "péikji"} “to bake” (velar stem in *k)
      %li *плак- → #{t "плайкьи", "pláikji"} “to cry” (velar stem in *k)
      %li *мог- → #{t "мойкьи", "móikji"} “to be able” (velar stem in *g)
    %p The three semivocalic stem subtypes, ending in *-uv, *-ij, or *-Cj (where C represents any other consonant), all vocalize when coming in contact with the infinitive ending.
    %ul
      %li *слув- → #{t "слути", "slúti"} “to be known for” (semivocalic stem in *uv)
      %li *кри- → #{t "крити", "kríti"} “to cover” (semivocalic stem in *ij)
      %li *пй- → #{t "пити", "píti"} “to drink” (semivocalic stem in *Cj)
      %li *рос-вй- → #{t "росуити", "rosuíti"} “to unfurl, evolve” (semivocalic stem in *Cj)
    %p In all other themeless verbs, collectively known as fleeting stems, the stem-final consonant is close completely when it comes in direct contact with the infinitive ending.
    %ul
      %li *жив- → #{t "жити", "źíti"} “to live” (fleeting stem with stem stress)
      %li *стан- → #{t "стати", "státi"} “to become” (fleeting stem with ending stress)
      %li *стар-ѣй- → #{t "старѣти", "starě́ti"} “to age, grow old” (fleeting stem with ending stress)
      %li *жен- → #{t "жети", "źéti"} “to harvest” (fleeting stem with ending stress)

= section "The Indicative Mood" do
  = section "The Formation of the Perfective" do
    %p As in several other Slavic languages, two processes must be discussed when it comes to the formation of perfective/imperfective pairs: perfectivization and deperfectivization.
    %p Perfectization is the process of deriving perfective verbs from primitive imperfectives. In Novegradian this is done overwhelmingly through the use of prefixes. The addition of a perfectivizing prefix may or may not change the meaning of the verb; in other words, prefixes serve both to form simple perfectives, and to derive new perfective verbs: #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write (#{abbrev 'impf'})” → #{t "напизати", "napizáti"} “write (#{abbrev 'pf'})”, #{t "опизати", "opizáti"} “describe (#{abbrev 'pf'})”, #{t "перепизати", "perepizáti"} “rewrite (#{abbrev 'pf'})”, etc.
    %p These prefixes are always derived from prepositions (although the prepositions they were derived from didn’t necessarily survive into modern Novegradian), usually ones that at one point had some sort of semantic connection with the root which has since been lost. Some of the more common prefixes include #{t "по-", "po-"} ‘confined to, along, by’, #{t "со-", "so-"} ‘with’, #{t "на-", "na-"} ‘on’, #{t "о-", "o-"} ‘at’, #{t "при-", "pri-"} ‘attached to’, #{t "за-", "za-"} ‘behind’, and #{t "про-", "pro-"} ‘through’. Examples, using some of the same roots as above:
    %ul
      %li #{t "цидати", "cidáti"} → #{t "процидати", "procidáti"} “read”
      %li #{t "видѣти", "víděti"} → #{t "овидѣти", "ovíděti"} “see”
      %li #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} → #{t "напизати", "napizáti"} “write”
    %p Non-native verbs almost exclusively use по- and за- to form simple perfectives:
    %ul
      %li #{t "гымати", "gýmati"} → #{t "загымати", "zagýmati"} “shout” (←Komi гым “thunder”)
      %li #{t "шецинити", "śéciniti"} → #{t "пошецинити", "pośéciniti"} “surrender” (←Komi шедöдчыны “give oneself up”)
      %li #{t "сарнити", "sarníti"} → #{t "посарнити", "posarníti"} “ramble” (←Komi сöрны “lie”)
      %li #{t "бомбардовати", "bombardováti"} → #{t "побомбардовати", "pobombardováti"} “bombard”
    %p Simple perfectivization, without change of meaning, can also be achieved by switching from the first to the second conjugation, or with the punctual suffix #{t "-н-", "-n-"}. Neither of these are productive, however.
    %ul
      %li #{t "брозати", "brozáti"} → #{t "брошити", "bróśiti"} “throw”
      %li #{t "рѣжати", "rěźáti"} → #{t "рѣжити", "rěźíti"} “decide”
      %li #{t "кажити", "kaźíti"} → #{t "кажнати", "kaźnáti"} “distort”
      %li #{t "лизати", "lízati"} → #{t "лизнати", "liznáti"} “lick”
    %p Finally, a handful of perfectives are simply irregular or suppletive:
    %ul
      %li #{t "наценати", "nacenáti"} → #{t "нашнати", "naśnáti"} “begin, start”
      %li #{t "брати", "bráti"} → #{t "женти", "źénti"} “bring” (cf. Common Slavic *brati, *vъzęti)
    %p In general, the pattern any given verb requires to form its perfective counterpart must be memorized. Even though prefixation is the most common method, it is not readily predictable which prefix is required to form the simple perfective without deriving a verb with a new meaning.
    %p In contrast, deperfectivization is the process by which a new imperfective form is created from a prefixed perfective verb, the result of the otherwise pairless derived perfectives that perfectivization creates. The vast majority of these forms, known as derived imperfectives, are formed with the suffix #{t "-ов-", "-ov"}, which is always first conjugation. This is the regular, productive pattern:
    %ul
      %li #{t "тулити", "tulíti"} “put away (#{abbrev 'impf'})” → #{t "затулити", "zatulíti"} “close (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "затуловати", "zatulováti"} “close (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
      %li #{t "пизати", "pizáti"} “write (#{abbrev 'impf'})” → #{t "препизати", "prepizáti"} “rewrite (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "преписовати", "prepisováti"} “rewrite (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
      %li #{t "концити", "kónciti"} “end (#{abbrev 'impf'})” → #{t "оконцити", "okónciti"} “graduate (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "оконцовати", "okoncováti"} “graduate (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
      %li #{t "еграти", "iegráti"} “play (#{abbrev 'impf'})” → #{t "вуийграти", "vuijgráti"} “win (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "вуийгровати", "vuijgrováti"} “win (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
      %li #{t "менѣти", "meně́ti"} “seem (#{abbrev 'impf'})” → #{t "соменѣти", "someně́ti"} “mention (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "соменовати", "somenováti"} “mention (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
    %p A less common pattern, which unproductively applies only to some second-conjugation verbs, is to palatalize the stem-final consonant and convert the verb to the first conjugation. Nowadays this pattern is rarely seen in verbs whose stems do not end in /v/; the preservation of this pattern may be due to a desire to avoid highly repetitive forms such as *<i>pozgodovováti</i>.
    %ul
      %li #{t "авити", "avíti"} “reveal (#{abbrev 'impf'})” → #{t "оявити", "oiavíti"} “declare (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "ояулати", "oiáulati"} “declare (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
      %li #{t "годовити", "godóviti"} “prepare (#{abbrev 'impf'})” → #{t "позгодовити", "pozgodóviti"} “train (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "позгодоулати", "pozgodóulati"} “train (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
      %li #{t "крѣпити", "krě́piti"} “make firm (#{abbrev 'impf'})” → #{t "позкрѣпити", "pozkrě́piti"} “fortify (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "позкрѣплати", "pozkrě́plati"} “fortify (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
    %p Finally, a small closed set of stems form the deperfective stem via ablaut. These are the verbs that show Indo-European Ø/E or Ø/O grade ablaut, with the Ø grade in the infinitive and the E/O grade in the present tense, such as #{t "брати", "bráti"} “to bring” ~ #{t "берун", "berún"} “I bring” and #{t "зуати", "zuáti"} “to call” ~ #{t "зовун", "zovún"} “I call”. In the deperfective stem, these verbs switch to the so-called neolengthened grade and acquire /i/ as the root vowel, while also switching to the first conjugation. While this is a nonproductive pattern, it is robust, with no evidence of regularization taking place even in colloquial usage.
    %ul
      %li #{t "брати", "bráti"} “bring (#{abbrev 'impf'})” → #{t "вуибрати", "vuibráti"} “pick out (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "вуибирати", "vuibiráti"} “pick out (#{abbrev 'impf'})”
      %li #{t "зуати", "zuáti"} “call (#{abbrev 'impf'})” → #{t "призуати", "prizuáti"} “invite (#{abbrev 'pf'})” → #{t "призивати", "priziváti"} “invite (#{abbrev 'impf'})”

  = section "The Present-Future Tense" do
    = section "The Regular Present/Future Tense" do
      %p The Present/Future tense inflects for person and number, with endings consisting of a theme vowel (in most cases) plus a suffix. The suffixes are broaly consistent across conjugations, with the exception of the first person singular, third person singular, and third person plural, which divide the set of endings into two broad subcategories: the M-Type (named for the #{abbrev '1sg'} ending in the first and athematic conjugations) and the UN-Type (named for the #{abbrev '1sg'} in the second and third conjugations. The table below shows the present/future endings for each conjugation:
      %table
        %tr
          %th
          %th 1Sg
          %th 2Sg
          %th 3Sg
          %th 1Dl
          %th 2Dl
          %th 3Dl
          %th 1Pl
          %th 2Pl
          %th 3Pl
        %tr
          %th A Conjugation
          %td= t("-а-м", "-a-m", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-а-ш", "-a-ś", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-a-ст", "-a-st", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-а-ва", "-a-va", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-а-ста", "-a-sta", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-а-ста", "-a-sta", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-а-ме", "-a-me", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-а-те", "-a-te", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-а-ти", "-a-ti", :linebreak => true)
        %tr
          %th I Conjugation
          %td= t("-Ø-ун", "-Ø-un", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-и-ш", "-i-ś", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-и-т", "-i-t", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-и-ва", "-i-va", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-и-та", "-i-ta", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-и-та", "-i-ta", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-и-м", "-i-m", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-и-те", "-i-te", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-Ø-ат", "-Ø-at", :linebreak => true)
        %tr
          %th E Conjugation
          %td= t("-Ø-ун", "-Ø-un", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-е-ш", "-e-ś", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-е-т", "-e-t", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-е-ва", "-e-va", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-е-та", "-e-ta", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-е-та", "-e-ta", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-е-м", "-e-m", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-е-те", "-e-te", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-Ø-ут", "-Ø-ut", :linebreak => true)
        %tr
          %th Athematic
          %td= t("-Ø-м", "-Ø-m", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-Ø-жи", "-Ø-źi", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-Ø-ст", "-Ø-st", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-Ø-ва", "-Ø-va", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-Ø-та", "-Ø-ta", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-Ø-та", "-Ø-ta", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-Ø-ме", "-Ø-me", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-Ø-те", "-Ø-te", :linebreak => true)
          %td= t("-Ø-ит", "-Ø-it", :linebreak => true)

      %p Note that the M-type endings -ст (#{abbrev '3sg'}) and -ати/-ит (#{abbrev '3pl'}) are pronounced /s/ and /a/ respectively. The spellings reflect a much older pronunciation.
      %p These endings may be attached to both perfective and imperfective verb stems. On perfective stems, they always indicate future action, while on imperfective stems they can indicate both present and future tenses depending on context; as with several other Slavic languages, aspect is a more fundamental distinction in Novegradian than tense.
      %p Note that the #{abbrev '1sg'} ending in the I-Conjugation and all endings in the E-Conjugation will predictably trigger palatalization if they come in contact with certain consonants in the stem#{footnote}. These changes are summarized below:
      %ul
