    = section "Irregularities in the A Conjugation" do
      %p The A Conjugation is for the most part extremely regular. The only irregularity in the present-future tense is the small set of so called j-stems, which end in /uj/ in the present but /ov/ in the infinitive. Such verbs were historically part of the E Conjugation, but transitioned to the A Conjugation possibly under the influence of the huge quantity of deperfectives that contain an identical (but coincidentally so) suffix /ov/. An example is #{t "ковати", "kóvati"} “forge”; the <i>-ui-</i> syllable is always stressed.
    - cyr = %w[к-у-ям к-у-яш к-у-яст к-у-ява к-у-яcта к-у-яcта к-у-яме к-у-яте к-у-яти]
    - lat = %w[kúiam kúiaś kúiast kúiava kúiasta kúiasta kúiame kúiate kúiati]
    = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "ковати", :lat => "kóvati"}, :meaning => "forge", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
    %p The above pattern applies only to cases where the <i>-ov-</i>/<i>-ui-</i> is actually a component of the root, not a derivational or deperfective suffix as in #{t "кѣловати", "kělováti"} “kiss”, which has a regular ending stress pattern in the present: #{t "кѣловам", "kělovám"}, #{t "кѣловаш", "kělováś"}, etc. In old texts or in poetry these verbs may appear in the E Conjugation with this <i>-ui-</i> suffix, but this is no longer valid in modern usage:
    - cyr = %w[кѣл-у-юн кѣл-у-еш кѣл-у-ет кѣл-у-ева кѣл-у-ета кѣл-у-ета кѣл-у-ем кѣл-у-ете кѣл-у-ют]
    - lat = %w[kělúiun kělúieś kělúiet kělúieva kělúieta kělúieta kělúiem kělúiete kělúiut]
    = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "кѣловати", :lat => "kělováti"}, :meaning => "kiss (arch.)", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat

    = section "Irregularities in the I Conjugation" do
      %p Despite the large number of stress patterns, the I Conjugation present-future is also quite regular. Distinctions seen in the infinitive, such as the different theme vowels i~ě~a, are neutralized, with all forms showing /i/. With #{t "криѕати", "kridzáti"} “shout”:
      - cyr = %w[криѕ-ун криѕ-иш криѕ-ит криѕ-ива криѕ-ита криѕ-ита криѕ-им криѕ-ите криѕ-ат]
      - lat = %w[kridzún kridzíś kridzít kridzíva kridzíta kridzíta kridzím kridzíte kridzát]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "криѕати", :lat => "kridzáti"}, :meaning => "shout", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      %p Sonantic stems do not display the metathesis seen in the infinitive; these forms are therefore regular, but the relationship to the infinitive may not be immediately obvious. With #{t "прети", "préti"} “force, pressure”:
      - cyr = %w[пер-ун пер-иш пер-ит пер-ива пер-ита пер-ита пер-им пер-ите пер-ат]
      - lat = %w[perún períś perít períva períta períta perím períte perát]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "прети", :lat => "préti"}, :meaning => "force, pressure", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      %p Some I and E conjugation verbs with the stem vowels /e/ and /o/ in the infinitive undergo ablaut in the present tense, with these vowels becoming /æ/ and /u/ respectively. If the following consonant is /sʲ/ or /zʲ/, these will depalatalize to /s/ and /z/. This change is known as the neoacute ablaut, the result of a now-lost pitch accent that emerged in late Common Slavic due to stress shifts. In modern Novegradian it is not always possible to predict when this change will occur; however, it is almost guaranteed when the verb has a proterodynamic or hysterodynamic stress pattern (i.e., one in which the first person singular has a different stress pattern than the rest of the present-future tense). Demonstrated below with #{t "ношити", "nóśiti"} “carry”:
      - cyr = %w[нуғь-ун нус-иш нус-ит нус-ива нус-ита нус-ита нус-им нус-ите нус-ат]
      - lat = %w[nuğjún núsiś núsit núsiva núsita núsita núsim núsite núsat]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "ношити", :lat => "nóśiti"}, :meaning => "carry", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat

    = section "Irregularities in the E Conjugation" do
      %p Most of the consonantal stems behave fairly regularly in the E Conjugation. Velar stems, such as #{t "плайкьи", "pláikji"} “cry”, are regular, showing palatalization throughout:
      - cyr = %w[плац-ун плац-еш плац-ет плац-ева плац-ета плац-ета плац-ем плац-ете плац-ут]
      - lat = %w[plácun pláceś plácet pláceva pláceta pláceta plácem plácete plácut]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "плайкьи", :lat => "pláikji"}, :meaning => "cry", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      %p Dental stems (#{t "исти", "ísti"} “go, walk”), fleeting stems (#{t "жити", "źíti"} “live”), and sonantic stems (#{t "мерети", "meréti"} “die”) are regular except for the lack of stem palatalization throughout.
      - cyr = %w[ид-ун ид-еш ид-ет ид-ева ид-ета ид-ета ид-ем ид-ете ид-ут]
      - lat = %w[idún idéś idét idéva idéta idéta idém idéte idút]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "исти", :lat => "ísti"}, :meaning => "go, walk", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      - cyr = %w[жив-ун жив-еш жив-ет жив-ева жив-ета жив-ета жив-ем жив-ете жив-ут]
      - lat = %w[źivún źivéś źivét źivéva źivéta źivéta źivém źivéte źivút]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "жити", :lat => "źíti"}, :meaning => "live", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      - cyr = %w[мер-ун мер-еш мер-ет мер-ева мер-ета мер-ета мер-ем мер-ете мер-ут]
      - lat = %w[merún meréś merét meréva meréta meréta merém meréte merút]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "мерети", :lat => "meréti"}, :meaning => "die", :aspect => "pf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      %p The three semivocalic stem types are regular from a phonemic perspective, though the *Cj type has some more complex spelling changes due to the different representations of consonant + yod sequences, alternating between using ю for /ju/ and ие for /je/. With #{t "плути", "plúti"} “swim” (*uv type), #{t "крити", "kríti"} “cover” (*ij type), and #{t "пити", "píti"} “drink” (*Cj type):
      - cyr = %w[плув-ун плув-еш плув-ет плув-ева плув-ета плув-ета плув-ем плув-ете плув-ут]
      - lat = %w[plúvun plúveś plúvet plúveva plúveta plúveta plúvem plúvete plúvut]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "плути", :lat => "plúti"}, :meaning => "swim", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      - cyr = %w[кри-юн кри-еш кри-ет кри-ева кри-ета кри-ета кри-ем кри-ете кри-ют]
      - lat = %w[kríjun kríjeś kríjet kríjeva kríjeta kríjeta kríjem kríjete kríjut]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "крити", :lat => "kríti"}, :meaning => "cover", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      - cyr = %w[п-юн пи-еш пи-ет пи-ева пи-ета пи-ета пи-ем пи-ете п-ют]
      - lat = %w[piún piéś piét piéva piéta piéta piém piéte piút]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "пити", :lat => "píti"}, :meaning => "drink", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      %p The ablauting stem type shows /e/ as the root vowel in the present-future, combined with ending stress. With #{t "брати", "bráti"} “bring, take”
      - cyr = %w[бер-ун бер-еш бер-ет бер-ева бер-ета бер-ета бер-ем бер-ете бер-ут]
      - lat = %w[berún beréś berét beréva beréta beréta berém beréte berút]
      = render 'present_future_verb_table', :infinitive => {:cyr => "брати", :lat => "bráit"}, :meaning => "bring, take", :aspect => "impf", :cyrillic => cyr, :latin => lat
      %p Neoacute patterns can also occur in the E Conjugation. In #{t "мойкьи", "móikji"} “be able to”, this causes the /g/ → /zʲ/ palatalization to then depalatalize to /z/:
      - cyr = %w[муз-ун муз-еш муз-ет муз-ева муз-ета муз-ета муз-ем муз-ете муз-ут]
      - lat = %w[múzun múześ múzet múzeva múzeta múzeta múzem múzete múzut]
